Justice Rilwan Aikawa of the Federal High Court in Lagos yesterday upheld that the Nigerian Army has no power under the nation’s constitution to subject civilians to ‘Operation Positive Identification’. Justice Aikawa made the declaration while delivering judgment on a Fundamental Rights Enforcement Suit instituted by human rights lawyer, Femi Falana (SAN) over the planned implementation of the exercise. While dismissing the preliminary objections filed by the Attorney General of the Federation and the Nigerian Army, the judge held that Falana has the locus standi to have instituted the suit. The judge further held that the fundamental rights of the Nigerian people to liberty and freedom of movement would be breached by the planned positive identification. Falana, a Senior Advocate of Nigeria (SAN), had filed the Fundamental Rights Enforcement suit on the 25th of October against the planned exercise by the army scheduled to hold from 1 November to 23 December 2019.